<% content_for :breadcrumbs do %>
  <li class="breadcrumb-item">Documentation</li>
  <li class="breadcrumb-item active" aria-current="page">Playground Guide</li>
<% end %>

<div class="docs-playground-guide">
  <!-- Header -->
  <div class="page-header" style="background-color: #EFF6FF; border-left: 4px solid #3B82F6; padding: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem;">
    <h1 style="color: #1E40AF; margin: 0;">
      <i class="bi bi-play-circle"></i> Playground Guide: Creating an Agent
    </h1>
    <p style="color: #1E40AF; margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0;">
      Step-by-step guide to creating and configuring AI agents using the PromptTracker Playground
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Quick Start -->
  <div class="alert alert-info mb-4">
    <h5><i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> What is the Playground?</h5>
    <p class="mb-0">
      The Playground is an interactive environment where you can design, test, and configure AI agents (prompts) before deploying them to production.
      It supports multiple LLM providers (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google) and various APIs (Chat Completions, Assistants, Responses).
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- Table of Contents -->
  <div class="card mb-4">
    <div class="card-header">
      <h5 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-list-ol"></i> Table of Contents</h5>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <ol class="mb-0">
        <li><a href="#step-1">Getting Started: Accessing the Playground</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-2">Choosing Your Provider and API</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-3">Writing Your Prompts</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-4">Configuring Model Settings</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-5">Adding Tools (Optional)</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-6">Working with Variables</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-7">Testing Your Agent</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-8">Structured Outputs (JSON Schema)</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-9">Saving Your Agent</a></li>
        <li><a href="#step-10">Syncing with OpenAI Assistants</a></li>
        <li><a href="#keyboard-shortcuts">Keyboard Shortcuts</a></li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 1: Getting Started -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-1">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-1-circle"></i> Getting Started: Accessing the Playground</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <h5>Option A: Create a New Agent (Standalone Mode)</h5>
      <ol>
        <li>Navigate to the <strong>Testing</strong> section from the main menu</li>
        <li>Click the <strong>"New Prompt"</strong> button in the top right</li>
        <li>Select <strong>"Create in Playground"</strong> from the dropdown</li>
        <li>You'll see a blank playground ready for configuration</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-4">Option B: Edit an Existing Agent</h5>
      <ol>
        <li>Go to <strong>Testing → Prompts</strong></li>
        <li>Click on any existing prompt</li>
        <li>Click the <strong>"Open in Playground"</strong> button</li>
        <li>The playground will load with the current version's configuration</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-4">Option C: Import from OpenAI</h5>
      <ol>
        <li>In the <strong>Testing</strong> dashboard, click <strong>"Sync OpenAI Assistants"</strong></li>
        <li>Your OpenAI assistants will be imported as prompts</li>
        <li>Open any imported prompt in the playground to edit it</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="alert alert-success mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> <strong>Tip:</strong> Use the standalone mode when creating a brand new agent from scratch.
        Use the edit mode when iterating on existing agents.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 2: Choosing Provider and API -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-2">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-2-circle"></i> Choosing Your Provider and API</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>The playground supports multiple LLM providers and APIs. Your choice determines which features are available.</p>

      <h5>1. Select a Provider</h5>
      <p>In the <strong>Model Configuration</strong> panel (right side), choose from:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>OpenAI</strong> - GPT models (gpt-4o, gpt-4o-mini, etc.)</li>
        <li><strong>Anthropic</strong> - Claude models (claude-3-5-sonnet, etc.)</li>
        <li><strong>Google</strong> - Gemini models</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="mt-3">2. Select an API</h5>
      <p>Different APIs offer different capabilities:</p>

      <div class="table-responsive">
        <table class="table table-bordered">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>API</th>
              <th>Provider</th>
              <th>Best For</th>
              <th>Features</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Chat Completions</strong></td>
              <td>OpenAI, Anthropic, Google</td>
              <td>Simple chat interactions, general-purpose agents</td>
              <td>System prompt, user prompt template, variables, tools</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Assistants</strong></td>
              <td>OpenAI</td>
              <td>Stateful conversations, file analysis, code execution</td>
              <td>Instructions, tools (file_search, code_interpreter), vector stores</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Responses</strong></td>
              <td>OpenAI</td>
              <td>Advanced multi-turn conversations</td>
              <td>System prompt, conversation testing, built-in tools</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h5 class="mt-3">3. Select a Model</h5>
      <p>After choosing provider and API, select the specific model:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>gpt-4o</strong> - Most capable OpenAI model, best for complex tasks</li>
        <li><strong>gpt-4o-mini</strong> - Faster and cheaper, good for simple tasks</li>
        <li><strong>claude-3-5-sonnet</strong> - Anthropic's most capable model</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> <strong>Note:</strong> The UI will automatically show/hide sections based on your API selection.
        For example, Assistants API shows only "Instructions" while Chat Completions shows "System Prompt" and "User Prompt Template".
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 3: Writing Prompts -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-3">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-3-circle"></i> Writing Your Prompts</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>The playground provides different prompt editors depending on your selected API:</p>

      <h5>For Chat Completions & Responses APIs:</h5>

      <h6 class="mt-3">System Prompt (Optional but Recommended)</h6>
      <p>The system prompt sets the AI's role, behavior, and guidelines. It's like giving the AI its job description.</p>

      <div class="card bg-light mb-3">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h6>Best Practices for System Prompts:</h6>
          <ul class="mb-0">
            <li>Use structured sections: <code>#role</code>, <code>#goal</code>, <code>#context</code>, <code>#tone_style</code>, <code>#guidelines</code></li>
            <li>Be specific about what the AI should and shouldn't do</li>
            <li>Define the expected tone and style</li>
            <li>Include examples of good responses if helpful</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <pre><code class="language-text">#role
You are a helpful customer support agent for an e-commerce platform.

#goal
Assist customers with order inquiries, returns, and general questions.

#tone_style
- Professional yet friendly
- Empathetic and patient
- Clear and concise

#guidelines
- Always verify order details before providing information
- Offer solutions, not just explanations
- Escalate to human agent if issue is complex
- Never share customer data with unauthorized parties</code></pre>

      <h6 class="mt-4">User Prompt Template (Required)</h6>
      <p>The user prompt template is the actual message sent to the AI. Use <code>{{ variable_name }}</code> syntax for dynamic content.</p>

      <pre><code class="language-text">Customer: {{ customer_name }}
Order ID: {{ order_id }}
Question: {{ customer_question }}

Please provide a helpful response to the customer's question.</code></pre>

      <h5 class="mt-4">For Assistants API:</h5>

      <h6>Instructions (Required)</h6>
      <p>Assistants use a single "Instructions" field that combines system-level guidance with task instructions.</p>

      <pre><code class="language-text">#role
You are a data analysis assistant with access to file search and code execution.

#capabilities
- Analyze CSV and Excel files
- Generate visualizations
- Perform statistical calculations
- Answer questions about uploaded data

#guidelines
- Always verify data before analysis
- Explain your methodology
- Provide visualizations when helpful
- Cite specific data points in your answers</code></pre>

      <h5 class="mt-4">AI-Powered Prompt Generation</h5>
      <p>Don't want to write prompts from scratch? Use the <strong>"Generate with AI"</strong> button!</p>

      <ol>
        <li>Click the <strong><i class="bi bi-magic"></i> Generate with AI</strong> button</li>
        <li>Describe what you want your agent to do in plain English</li>
        <li>The AI will generate a complete prompt with proper structure</li>
        <li>Review and edit the generated prompt as needed</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-stars"></i> <strong>Enhancement Mode:</strong> If you already have content in your prompts, the button changes to
        "Enhance with AI" and will suggest specific improvements rather than generating from scratch.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 4: Model Settings -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-4">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-4-circle"></i> Configuring Model Settings</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>Fine-tune your agent's behavior with these settings in the <strong>Model Configuration</strong> panel:</p>

      <h5>Basic Settings</h5>
      <div class="table-responsive">
        <table class="table table-bordered">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Setting</th>
              <th>Range</th>
              <th>Description</th>
              <th>Recommendation</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Temperature</strong></td>
              <td>0.0 - 2.0</td>
              <td>Controls randomness and creativity</td>
              <td>
                <strong>0.0-0.3:</strong> Factual, consistent responses<br>
                <strong>0.7-1.0:</strong> Balanced creativity<br>
                <strong>1.5-2.0:</strong> Very creative, unpredictable
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Max Tokens</strong></td>
              <td>1 - model limit</td>
              <td>Maximum length of response</td>
              <td>
                <strong>256:</strong> Short answers<br>
                <strong>1024:</strong> Medium responses<br>
                <strong>4096+:</strong> Long-form content
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Top P</strong></td>
              <td>0.0 - 1.0</td>
              <td>Alternative to temperature (nucleus sampling)</td>
              <td>
                <strong>0.9-1.0:</strong> Standard (use with temperature)<br>
                <strong>0.1-0.5:</strong> More focused (don't use with low temperature)
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> <strong>Important:</strong> Don't set both temperature and top_p to extreme values.
        Use temperature for most cases, and leave top_p at 1.0.
      </div>

      <h5 class="mt-4">Advanced Settings</h5>
      <p>Click <strong>"Advanced Options"</strong> to access additional settings:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Frequency Penalty</strong> (0.0-2.0) - Reduces repetition of tokens based on frequency</li>
        <li><strong>Presence Penalty</strong> (0.0-2.0) - Encourages talking about new topics</li>
        <li><strong>Stop Sequences</strong> - Custom strings that stop generation</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 5: Adding Tools -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-5">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-5-circle"></i> Adding Tools (Optional)</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>Tools extend your agent's capabilities beyond text generation. Available tools depend on your selected API.</p>

      <h5>Built-in Tools</h5>

      <h6 class="mt-3"><i class="bi bi-search"></i> File Search (Assistants & Responses APIs)</h6>
      <p>Allows the agent to search through uploaded documents and files.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>In the <strong>Tools</strong> section, click the <strong>File Search</strong> card to enable it</li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Configure Vector Stores"</strong></li>
        <li>Either select existing vector stores or create a new one</li>
        <li>Upload files (PDF, TXT, DOCX, etc.) to the vector store</li>
        <li>The agent can now search and reference these files</li>
      </ol>

      <h6 class="mt-3"><i class="bi bi-code-square"></i> Code Interpreter (Assistants API)</h6>
      <p>Enables the agent to write and execute Python code.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Click the <strong>Code Interpreter</strong> card to enable it</li>
        <li>The agent can now perform calculations, data analysis, and generate visualizations</li>
        <li>Useful for math, data processing, and chart generation</li>
      </ol>

      <h6 class="mt-3"><i class="bi bi-globe"></i> Web Search (Responses API)</h6>
      <p>Allows the agent to search the web for current information.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Click the <strong>Web Search</strong> card to enable it</li>
        <li>The agent can now fetch real-time information from the internet</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-4">Custom Functions (Advanced)</h5>
      <p>Define custom functions that the agent can call to interact with your application.</p>

      <ol>
        <li>In the Tools section, click <strong>"Add Function"</strong></li>
        <li>Define the function schema:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Name:</strong> Function identifier (e.g., "get_order_status")</li>
            <li><strong>Description:</strong> What the function does (helps the AI decide when to call it)</li>
            <li><strong>Parameters:</strong> JSON Schema defining the function's inputs</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>In your application code, implement the function handler</li>
        <li>The agent will call this function when needed</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="card bg-light mt-3">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h6>Example Function Definition:</h6>
          <pre><code class="language-json">{
  "name": "get_order_status",
  "description": "Retrieves the current status of a customer order",
  "parameters": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "order_id": {
        "type": "string",
        "description": "The unique order identifier"
      }
    },
    "required": ["order_id"]
  }
}</code></pre>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert alert-success mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> <strong>Tip:</strong> Start without tools and add them only when needed.
        Tools add complexity and can increase response time.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 6: Variables -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-6">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-6-circle"></i> Working with Variables</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>Variables make your prompts dynamic and reusable. They're automatically detected from your prompt templates.</p>

      <h5>Defining Variables in Your Prompt</h5>
      <p>Use the <code>{{ variable_name }}</code> syntax anywhere in your user prompt template:</p>

      <pre><code class="language-text">Hello {{ customer_name }},

Thank you for contacting us about {{ issue_type }}.
Your order {{ order_id }} is currently {{ order_status }}.</code></pre>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Variable Schema (Auto-Generated)</h5>
      <p>The playground automatically detects variables and creates a schema in the <strong>Variables</strong> panel:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Each variable is listed with its name</li>
        <li>You can set the type (string, number, boolean, array, object)</li>
        <li>Mark variables as required or optional</li>
        <li>Add descriptions to help other developers</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Testing with Sample Values</h5>
      <p>In the Variables panel, you can enter sample values to test your prompt:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Fill in sample values for each variable</li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Preview"</strong> to see the rendered prompt</li>
        <li>The preview shows exactly what will be sent to the LLM</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Tip:</strong> Use descriptive variable names like <code>customer_email</code> instead of <code>email</code>
        to make your prompts more maintainable.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 7: Testing -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-7">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-7-circle"></i> Testing Your Agent</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>The playground provides multiple ways to test your agent before deploying it.</p>

      <h5>Preview Mode (Template-based APIs)</h5>
      <p>For Chat Completions and similar APIs:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Fill in sample values in the <strong>Variables</strong> panel</li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Preview"</strong></li>
        <li>See the fully rendered prompt with variables replaced</li>
        <li>Verify the prompt looks correct before testing</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Conversation Testing (Responses & Assistants APIs)</h5>
      <p>For APIs that support multi-turn conversations:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Look for the <strong>Conversation</strong> panel (appears automatically for supported APIs)</li>
        <li>Type a message in the input field</li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Send"</strong> or press Enter</li>
        <li>The agent will respond based on your configuration</li>
        <li>Continue the conversation to test multi-turn interactions</li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Reset"</strong> to start a new conversation</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-3">What to Test</h5>
      <div class="card bg-light">
        <div class="card-body">
          <h6>Testing Checklist:</h6>
          <ul class="mb-0">
            <li><strong>Edge Cases:</strong> Test with unusual or extreme inputs</li>
            <li><strong>Variable Combinations:</strong> Try different variable values</li>
            <li><strong>Tone & Style:</strong> Verify the response matches your guidelines</li>
            <li><strong>Tool Usage:</strong> If using tools, verify they're called appropriately</li>
            <li><strong>Error Handling:</strong> Test with missing or invalid data</li>
            <li><strong>Response Length:</strong> Check if max_tokens is appropriate</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> <strong>Note:</strong> Playground testing uses real API calls and consumes tokens.
        Monitor your usage to avoid unexpected costs.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 8: Structured Outputs -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-8">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-8-circle"></i> Structured Outputs (JSON Schema)</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>Structured outputs guarantee that the LLM response matches a specific JSON schema. This is useful for:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Extracting structured data from text</li>
        <li>Ensuring consistent response formats</li>
        <li>Integrating with downstream systems</li>
        <li>Building reliable APIs</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Configuring Structured Outputs</h5>
      <ol>
        <li>In the Model Configuration panel, expand <strong>"Advanced Options"</strong></li>
        <li>Expand the <strong>"Structured Output (JSON Schema)"</strong> section</li>
        <li>Define your JSON Schema in the textarea</li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Validate JSON"</strong> to check syntax</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Example: Sentiment Analysis</h5>
      <pre><code class="language-json">{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "sentiment": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["positive", "negative", "neutral"],
      "description": "The overall sentiment of the text"
    },
    "confidence": {
      "type": "number",
      "minimum": 0,
      "maximum": 1,
      "description": "Confidence score between 0 and 1"
    },
    "key_phrases": {
      "type": "array",
      "items": {
        "type": "string"
      },
      "description": "Important phrases that influenced the sentiment"
    }
  },
  "required": ["sentiment", "confidence"],
  "additionalProperties": false
}</code></pre>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Example: Data Extraction</h5>
      <pre><code class="language-json">{
  "type": "object",
  "properties": {
    "customer_name": {
      "type": "string"
    },
    "order_id": {
      "type": "string",
      "pattern": "^ORD-[0-9]{6}$"
    },
    "issue_category": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["shipping", "refund", "product_quality", "other"]
    },
    "urgency": {
      "type": "string",
      "enum": ["low", "medium", "high"]
    }
  },
  "required": ["customer_name", "issue_category", "urgency"]
}</code></pre>

      <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> <strong>Supported Models:</strong> Structured outputs work with OpenAI gpt-4o models and Anthropic Claude 3+.
        Check the <a href="https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/structured-outputs" target="_blank">OpenAI documentation</a> for details.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 9: Saving -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-9">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-9-circle"></i> Saving Your Agent</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>Once you're happy with your agent configuration, it's time to save it.</p>

      <h5>Saving a New Agent (Standalone Mode)</h5>
      <ol>
        <li>Click the <strong>"Create Prompt"</strong> button</li>
        <li>A modal will appear asking for:
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Prompt Name:</strong> A descriptive name (e.g., "Customer Support Agent")</li>
            <li><strong>Slug:</strong> Auto-generated URL-friendly identifier (e.g., "customer_support_agent")</li>
            <li><strong>Notes:</strong> Optional description of this version</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Save"</strong></li>
        <li>You'll be redirected to the prompt's detail page</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Updating an Existing Agent</h5>
      <p>When editing an existing prompt, the save behavior depends on the version's state:</p>

      <div class="table-responsive">
        <table class="table table-bordered">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Version State</th>
              <th>Condition</th>
              <th>Save Behavior</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="badge bg-secondary">Development</span></td>
              <td>No tests, datasets, or production responses</td>
              <td><strong>Updates in place</strong> - Changes are saved to the current version</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="badge bg-warning">Testing</span></td>
              <td>Has tests or datasets</td>
              <td><strong>Conditional:</strong> Non-structural changes update in place, structural changes create new version</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><span class="badge bg-success">Production</span></td>
              <td>Has production responses (tracked calls)</td>
              <td><strong>Always creates new version</strong> - Original version is immutable</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h6 class="mt-3">Structural vs Non-Structural Changes</h6>
      <p><strong>Structural changes</strong> (force new version in Testing state):</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Provider, API, or model changes</li>
        <li>Tool configuration changes</li>
        <li>Variables schema changes</li>
        <li>Response schema changes</li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>Non-structural changes</strong> (can update in place):</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Prompt text edits</li>
        <li>Temperature, max_tokens, and other parameters</li>
        <li>Notes and descriptions</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="alert alert-success mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> <strong>Best Practice:</strong> Add meaningful notes when creating new versions to track what changed and why.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Step 10: Syncing with OpenAI -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="step-10">
    <div class="card-header bg-primary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-10-circle"></i> Syncing with OpenAI Assistants</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>If you're using the OpenAI Assistants API, you can sync your agent with OpenAI's platform.</p>

      <h5>Push to OpenAI (Create/Update Assistant)</h5>
      <p>Send your local configuration to OpenAI to create or update an assistant:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Configure your agent in the playground with <strong>Provider: OpenAI</strong> and <strong>API: Assistants</strong></li>
        <li>Click the <strong>"Push to OpenAI"</strong> button in the sync section</li>
        <li>If no assistant exists, a new one will be created</li>
        <li>If an assistant already exists (has assistant_id), it will be updated</li>
        <li>The assistant_id is stored in the version's metadata</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Pull from OpenAI (Import Changes)</h5>
      <p>Fetch the latest configuration from an existing OpenAI assistant:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Click the <strong>"Pull from OpenAI"</strong> button</li>
        <li>The latest configuration from OpenAI will be fetched</li>
        <li>Your local version will be updated with the remote changes</li>
        <li>The page will reload to show the updated configuration</li>
      </ol>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Bulk Import Assistants</h5>
      <p>Import all your OpenAI assistants at once:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Go to the <strong>Testing</strong> dashboard</li>
        <li>Click <strong>"Sync OpenAI Assistants"</strong></li>
        <li>All assistants from your OpenAI account will be imported as prompts</li>
        <li>Each assistant becomes a prompt with one version</li>
        <li>You can then edit them in the playground</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="alert alert-info mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> <strong>Sync Status:</strong> The playground shows sync status indicators:
        <ul class="mb-0">
          <li><span class="badge bg-success">Synced</span> - Local and remote are in sync</li>
          <li><span class="badge bg-warning">Modified</span> - Local changes not pushed</li>
          <li><span class="badge bg-secondary">Not Synced</span> - Never synced with OpenAI</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="alert alert-warning mt-3">
        <i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> <strong>Important:</strong> Pushing to OpenAI requires a valid OpenAI API key configured in your PromptTracker settings.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Keyboard Shortcuts -->
  <div class="card mb-4" id="keyboard-shortcuts">
    <div class="card-header bg-secondary text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-keyboard"></i> Keyboard Shortcuts</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <p>Speed up your workflow with these keyboard shortcuts:</p>

      <div class="table-responsive">
        <table class="table table-bordered">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Action</th>
              <th>Shortcut</th>
              <th>Context</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Save</td>
              <td><kbd>Cmd/Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>S</kbd></td>
              <td>Anywhere in playground</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Preview</td>
              <td><kbd>Cmd/Ctrl</kbd> + <kbd>P</kbd></td>
              <td>When variables are filled</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Send Message</td>
              <td><kbd>Enter</kbd></td>
              <td>In conversation input</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>New Line</td>
              <td><kbd>Shift</kbd> + <kbd>Enter</kbd></td>
              <td>In conversation input</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Tab Indent</td>
              <td><kbd>Tab</kbd></td>
              <td>In JSON editors (response schema, functions)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Show Shortcuts</td>
              <td><kbd>?</kbd></td>
              <td>Anywhere in playground</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="alert alert-info">
        <i class="bi bi-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Tip:</strong> Press <kbd>?</kbd> in the playground to see all available shortcuts.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Best Practices -->
  <div class="card mb-4">
    <div class="card-header bg-success text-white">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-star"></i> Best Practices & Tips</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <h5>Prompt Engineering</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Use structured sections (#role, #goal, #guidelines) for clarity</li>
        <li>Be specific about what you want and don't want</li>
        <li>Include examples of good responses when helpful</li>
        <li>Test with edge cases and unusual inputs</li>
        <li>Iterate based on real-world results</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Configuration</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Start with default settings (temperature: 0.7, top_p: 1.0)</li>
        <li>Lower temperature (0.0-0.3) for factual, consistent responses</li>
        <li>Higher temperature (1.0-1.5) for creative tasks</li>
        <li>Set appropriate max_tokens to avoid truncation</li>
        <li>Use structured outputs for reliable data extraction</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Tools</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Only enable tools you actually need</li>
        <li>Test tool usage thoroughly before production</li>
        <li>Provide clear function descriptions to help the AI</li>
        <li>Monitor tool usage costs (file_search, code_interpreter)</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Version Management</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Add meaningful notes when creating versions</li>
        <li>Test thoroughly before activating a version</li>
        <li>Use the Testing section to validate before production</li>
        <li>Monitor production responses in the Monitoring section</li>
        <li>Set up auto-evaluators to catch issues early</li>
      </ul>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Cost Optimization</h5>
      <ul>
        <li>Use cheaper models (gpt-4o-mini) for simple tasks</li>
        <li>Set appropriate max_tokens to avoid waste</li>
        <li>Cache system prompts when possible</li>
        <li>Monitor token usage in the Monitoring section</li>
        <li>Test with smaller datasets before scaling</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Common Issues -->
  <div class="card mb-4">
    <div class="card-header bg-warning">
      <h3 class="mb-0"><i class="bi bi-exclamation-triangle"></i> Common Issues & Solutions</h3>
    </div>
    <div class="card-body">
      <h5>Issue: Variables not detected</h5>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Make sure you're using the correct syntax: <code>{{ variable_name }}</code> with double curly braces and spaces.</p>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Issue: Preview shows "unfilled variables"</h5>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Fill in all required variables in the Variables panel before clicking Preview.</p>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Issue: Tools not appearing</h5>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Tools are only available for certain APIs. Check that you've selected an API that supports tools (Chat Completions, Assistants, Responses).</p>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Issue: Can't update existing version</h5>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> If the version has production responses, it's immutable. Your changes will create a new version instead.</p>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Issue: Structured output validation fails</h5>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Click "Validate JSON" to check your schema syntax. Make sure it's valid JSON Schema format.</p>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Issue: Sync to OpenAI fails</h5>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Verify your OpenAI API key is configured correctly in the PromptTracker settings. Check that you have permission to create/modify assistants.</p>

      <h5 class="mt-3">Issue: Response is truncated</h5>
      <p><strong>Solution:</strong> Increase the max_tokens setting in Model Configuration → Advanced Options.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Next Steps -->
  <div class="alert alert-success">
    <h5><i class="bi bi-check-circle"></i> Next Steps</h5>
    <p>Now that you've created your agent, here's what to do next:</p>
    <ol class="mb-0">
      <li><strong>Create Tests:</strong> Go to the Testing section and create test cases for your agent</li>
      <li><strong>Set Up Datasets:</strong> Create datasets with various input scenarios</li>
      <li><strong>Run Test Runs:</strong> Execute your tests to validate behavior</li>
      <li><strong>Activate Version:</strong> Once satisfied, activate your version for production use</li>
      <li><strong>Integrate in Code:</strong> Use <code>PromptTracker::LlmCallService.track</code> to call your agent from your application</li>
      <li><strong>Configure Auto-Evaluators:</strong> Set up automatic evaluation of production calls</li>
      <li><strong>Monitor Performance:</strong> Track usage, costs, and quality in the Monitoring section</li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <!-- Footer Links -->
  <div class="text-center mt-4">
    <div class="btn-group" role="group">
      <%= link_to testing_root_path, class: "btn btn-primary" do %>
        <i class="bi bi-arrow-left"></i> Back to Testing
      <% end %>
      <%= link_to testing_playground_path, class: "btn btn-success" do %>
        <i class="bi bi-play-circle"></i> Open Playground
      <% end %>
      <%= link_to docs_tracking_path, class: "btn btn-outline-secondary" do %>
        <i class="bi bi-book"></i> Integration Guide
      <% end %>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
